<Base title="ʿAqīdah differences" compactHeader={true} toc={toc}>
  <p class="ar-title" lang="ar" dir="rtl">الفروق العقدية</p>
  <h2>ʿAqīdah differences</h2>
  <p class="summary">A comparative reading of the three flashpoints between Salafī ʿaqīdah and the classical Ashʿarī/Māturīdī Sunnī ʿaqīdah: the divine attributes, the relationship between literal and interpretive reading of mutashābih texts, and the legitimacy of kalām as a discipline.</p>

  <h3 id="shared">The shared ground</h3>
  <p>Before the disagreements, the agreement: both sides affirm the absolute oneness of Allāh (<em>tawḥīd</em>), the transcendence of Allāh above any resemblance to created things (<em>tanzīh</em> or <em>laysa ka-mithlihi shayʾ</em>), the obligation to affirm everything the Qurʾān and authentic Sunnah affirm, and the impermissibility of describing Allāh in terms not found in the texts. Both sides reject anthropomorphism (<em>tashbīh</em>) and corporealism (<em>tajsīm</em>) as creedal errors. The disagreement is on how to read certain texts about the divine attributes that, taken at face value in human language, would imply something Allāh has explicitly denied of Himself.</p>

  <h3 id="attributes">1. The divine attributes (al-Ṣifāt)</h3>
  <p>The Qurʾān and Sunnah ascribe to Allāh attributes that, in their apparent linguistic meaning, would parallel attributes of created things — a "hand" (<em>yad</em>), a "face" (<em>wajh</em>), a "settling on the Throne" (<em>istiwāʾ</em> ʿalā al-ʿarsh), a "descent" (<em>nuzūl</em>) in the last third of the night. Both schools affirm that these texts are revealed and must be accepted; the question is how their meaning is to be understood given the verse <em>laysa ka-mithlihi shayʾ</em> ("there is nothing like Him") (Q 42:11).</p>

  <p><strong>The Salafī position.</strong> The Salafī school affirms each divine attribute in its apparent linguistic meaning, with the qualification "<em>bilā kayf</em>" — "without [knowing] the modality." That is: Allāh has a hand, a face, an <em>istiwāʾ</em> on the Throne — but the modality (<em>kayfiyya</em>) of these attributes is not knowable to created intellects, and is not to be likened to that of created things. The Salafī school rejects ta'wīl (interpretive reading away from the apparent meaning) as well as <em>tafwīḍ</em> in the form that consigns the meaning itself to Allāh's knowledge. The position traces to Imam Aḥmad, and is reflected in the phrase narrated from Imam Mālik — "the <em>istiwāʾ</em> is known, how it is is unknown, asking about it is an innovation."</p>
  <Quote
    author="IslamQA.info (Shaykh Muḥammad Ṣāliḥ al-Munajjid)"
    site="IslamQA.info"
    sourceType="salafi"
    url="https://islamqa.info/en/answers/249293"
    excerpt="It is obligatory to believe in the names and attributes that Allah has affirmed for Himself and what His Messenger has affirmed of that, without asking how, likening Him to His creation, distorting the meaning or denying any of it. So we know the attributes in one way, but we do not know them in another way. We know them as far as they are affirmed, and we know what they mean, but we do not know how they are or what their real nature is."
  />

  <p><strong>The classical Sunnī (Ashʿarī/Māturīdī) position.</strong> The classical schools affirm the same texts as revealed truth, but read the apparent linguistic meanings of words like "hand" or "face" as either: (a) consigned to Allāh's knowledge — <em>tafwīḍ al-maʿnā</em> — without specifying any meaning that would imply corporeality, this being the position attributed to the Salaf themselves; or (b) interpreted in a contextually appropriate non-literal sense — <em>ta'wīl</em> — when the literal reading would imply <em>tashbīh</em> (e.g., reading "hand" as "power" or "favour" — uses already established in classical Arabic and the Qurʾān itself, as in Q 5:64 "<em>bal yadāhu mabsūṭatān</em>"). Both options preserve the overriding principle of <em>tanzīh</em>.</p>
  <Quote
    author="Shaykh Farāz Rabbānī"
    site="SeekersGuidance"
    sourceType="classical-sunni"
    url="https://seekersguidance.org/answers/islamic-belief/the-asharis-maturidis-standards-of-mainstream-sunni-beliefs/"
    excerpt="Affirming what Allah has affirmed, such as istiwa' or His Hand or Eyes, not more and not less. Negating what Allah has decisively negated, which is any similitude whatsoever between the Creator and creation — a negation that the sound intellect readily discerns, and which was affirmed by Allah's words, 'There is absolutely nothing like unto Him.' Consigning (tafwid) the specific meaning and details of such matters to Allah Most High."
  />

  <p><strong>Where the Salafī position runs into difficulty.</strong> The position holds that the apparent linguistic meaning of "yad," "wajh," "istiwāʾ," "nuzūl" is real, qualified by <em>bilā kayf</em> — without modality. The internal difficulty: the apparent linguistic meaning of "yad" in Arabic is a body-part. To say "the apparent meaning is real but not like a created hand" is either to perform ta'wīl (specifying that the meaning is not the literal body-part — which the position formally rejects) or to leave the affirmation contentless (the meaning is the apparent one, but it is not what the apparent one signifies — which is contradictory). The classical Sunnī position resolves this by either <em>tafwīḍ</em> (declining to specify a meaning at all) or by <em>ta'wīl</em> (specifying a non-body-part meaning that classical Arabic supports — e.g., "yad" as "power" or "favour," the same usage Q 5:64 employs in <em>yadāhu mabsūṭatān</em>). The Salafī position rejects both resolutions while needing one of them to avoid either contradiction or anthropomorphism.</p>

  <h3 id="interpretive">2. Literal vs. interpretive (Ẓāhir vs. Ta'wīl)</h3>
  <p>The deeper question is hermeneutic. Both sides agree that some Qurʾānic passages are <em>muḥkam</em> (clear in meaning) and others <em>mutashābih</em> (susceptible to multiple meanings, requiring qualification). The disagreement is about what the right response to a mutashābih verse is.</p>

  <p><strong>The Salafī position.</strong> The Salafī school argues that the apparent (<em>ẓāhir</em>) meaning of a Qurʾānic word is its actual meaning unless an explicit textual indicator says otherwise. To depart from the <em>ẓāhir</em> without such an indicator is <em>taḥrīf</em> — distortion. Therefore, where the Qurʾān or authentic Sunnah affirms a divine attribute in apparent terms, that attribute is real in the apparent linguistic sense — only the <em>kayfiyya</em> is unknown. The IslamQA.info answer on this point is unambiguous:</p>
  <Quote
    author="IslamQA.info (Shaykh Muḥammad Ṣāliḥ al-Munajjid)"
    site="IslamQA.info"
    sourceType="salafi"
    url="https://islamqa.info/en/answers/151794"
    excerpt="Every divine attribute that is mentioned in a saheeh text must be affirmed. In principle, words are to be understood in a real sense, unless the ummah is unanimously agreed that something is not to be understood in a real sense, and is rather a metaphor, because there is no way to follow what has been revealed to us from our Lord except on that basis. Whoever interprets all the divine attributes in a manner other than their apparent meaning, and regards the words as metaphorical, that will inevitably lead him to denying the Lord and likening Him to something non-existent."
  />

  <p><strong>The classical Sunnī position.</strong> The classical schools argue that the verse <em>laysa ka-mithlihi shayʾ</em> is itself an explicit textual indicator: any apparent meaning that would, if taken literally, place Allāh in the same category as created things must be qualified. This is not <em>taḥrīf</em>; it is the application of a Qurʾānic principle to other Qurʾānic verses. The Ashʿarī and Māturīdī schools further argue that the language of the Qurʾān itself uses metaphor (<em>majāz</em>) extensively, and that recognising figurative usage where context demands it is the very methodology that the Companions and Salaf used implicitly when they did not, for example, claim Allāh has a literal physical hand. Crucially, both <em>tafwīḍ</em> and <em>ta'wīl</em> affirm what Allāh has affirmed — they differ only on whether the specific meaning is knowable to us, not on whether the attribute is real.</p>
  <Quote
    author="Shaykh Farāz Rabbānī"
    site="SeekersGuidance"
    sourceType="classical-sunni"
    url="https://seekersguidance.org/answers/islamic-belief/the-asharis-maturidis-standards-of-mainstream-sunni-beliefs/"
    excerpt="They did not affirm more than that and did not insist on understanding such affirmations in being 'literal' in nature. This is because the literal (i.e. primary) meaning of such matters entails affirming similitude between the Creator and creation and such similitude has been clearly and decisively negated throughout the Qur'an. When the need for it arose, some of the early Muslim (salaf) scholars and many of the later Muslim (khalaf) scholars used figurative interpretation to give a meaning to such 'apparently problematic' primary texts, using the sound principles of linguistic usage and textual interpretation."
  />

  <p><strong>Where the Salafī position runs into difficulty.</strong> The position requires the <em>ẓāhir</em> to be the operative meaning unless an explicit textual indicator says otherwise. The verse <em>laysa ka-mithlihi shayʾ</em> (Q 42:11) is itself such an indicator: it explicitly negates likeness to anything created. The Salafī methodology accepts this verse as muḥkam yet does not allow it to qualify the apparent linguistic meanings of attributes that, taken literally, would imply likeness to created things. The classical Sunnī methodology applies <em>laysa ka-mithlihi shayʾ</em> as the governing principle and reads other passages in light of it; this is not <em>taḥrīf</em>, it is the Qurʾān interpreting itself. The Salafī position has not articulated a principled reason why this particular Qurʾānic principle does not function as the indicator it appears to be.</p>

  <p><strong>The al-Ibāna question.</strong> A frequent Salafī claim — that Imam al-Ashʿarī "returned to" Atharī creed at the end of his life, citing <em>al-Ibāna ʿan Uṣūl al-Diyāna</em> — has been examined at scholarly length and rebutted. The ḥadīth master Ibn ʿAsākir's <em>Tabyīn Kadhib al-Muftarī fī mā Nusiba ilā al-Imām al-Ashʿarī</em> documents that the chains of narration for the attributed recantation contain liars in every link. Imam al-Kawtharī in <em>al-Sayf al-Ṣaqīl</em> (p. 108) notes that <em>al-Ibāna</em> was written <em>early</em> — right after al-Ashʿarī's break from Muʿtazilism — and was an attempt to induce the Ḥanbalī literalist al-Barbahārī (d. 328 AH) to embrace mainstream Sunnī tenets, not a final-life recantation. Ḥāfiẓ al-Dhahabī corroborates this in <em>Siyar Aʿlām al-Nubalāʾ</em> 15.90. The text of <em>al-Ibāna</em> itself uses kalām-style argumentation throughout — the very methodology the citation is meant to disavow.</p>

  <h3 id="kalam">3. The role of kalām (dialectical theology)</h3>
  <p>Kalām is the discipline of using rational argument to defend creedal claims. It emerged in the late 2nd / early 3rd Hijri century in response to the Muʿtazila and the influx of Greek philosophy into the Muslim world. Both Ashʿarism and Māturīdism are kalām schools.</p>

  <p><strong>The Salafī position.</strong> The Salafī movement classifies kalām as a blameworthy innovation. The argument: the Companions and the early Salaf did not engage in dialectical theology, and the discipline is liable to lead its practitioners into philosophical errors that the simple textual creed of the Salaf would have avoided. Ibn Taymiyya's <em>Darʾ Taʿāruḍ al-ʿAql wa-l-Naql</em> ("Repulsing the Conflict between Reason and Revelation") is the foundational Salafī treatment of this stance. Imam al-Shāfiʿī's statement — "whoever occupies himself with kalām is likely to go astray" — is frequently cited; the Salafī position takes this as a general condemnation of the discipline rather than a contextual caution. <em>(No verbatim online Salafī source with a confirmed URL could be located at time of writing; a source will be added when one is verified.)</em></p>

  <p><strong>The classical Sunnī position.</strong> The classical schools argue that kalām became necessary at the moment in Islamic history when philosophical and rationalist challenges began to be levelled against the religion publicly. To leave such challenges unanswered would be to abandon the religion to its critics; to answer them effectively requires the same conceptual vocabulary the critics use. Imam al-Ghazālī's <em>Iḥyāʾ ʿUlūm al-Dīn</em> classifies kalām as <em>farḍ kifāyah</em> — a communal obligation incumbent on enough Muslims to defend the creed publicly, though not on every individual believer. The Ashʿarī and Māturīdī kalām produced the most rigorous Sunnī defenses against Muʿtazilism, the philosophers (<em>falāsifa</em>), and later European rationalism; without them, mainstream Sunnism would have had no formal theological apparatus to meet those challenges with.</p>
  <Quote
    author="Shaykh Dr. Muḥammad Abū Bakr Badhib"
    site="SeekersGuidance"
    sourceType="classical-sunni"
    url="https://seekersguidance.org/category/answers/islamic-belief/?s=kalam"
    excerpt="It is a communal obligation upon scholars and their students to ward off innovators' harm and protect the Islamic creed from foreign thoughts. The individual obligation applies to those affected by heretical beliefs that cannot be refuted except through engaging in this science. His contributions to the science of ʿAqīda alone include more than ten published works, excluding unpublished or unknown ones."
  />

  <p><strong>Where the Salafī position runs into difficulty.</strong> The position holds that <em>kalām</em> is an illegitimate innovation, foreign to the Salaf's methodology. The internal difficulty: the foundational Salafī polemical works are themselves exercises in <em>kalām</em> in the technical sense — using rational argument to defend creedal claims against philosophical and inter-religious challenges. Ibn Taymiyya's <em>Darʾ Taʿāruḍ al-ʿAql wa-l-Naql</em> is structured around the relationship between reason and revelation — a classic kalām question, treated in classic kalām terms. Ibn al-Qayyim's <em>al-Ṣawāʿiq al-Mursala</em> is a substantial kalām engagement with the Jahmiyya. The position rejects in principle what it deploys in practice when the philosophical challenges arise. The classical Sunnī position — that kalām is <em>farḍ kifāyah</em>, a communal obligation when the religion is challenged philosophically — describes more accurately what the Salafī tradition actually does.</p>

  <h3 id="pattern">The pattern</h3>
  <p>The three difficulties above share a structure. Each presents the Salafī position with a methodological principle the position holds in theory: the apparent meaning is the operative meaning; explicit textual indicators are required to depart from the apparent meaning; <em>kalām</em> is foreign to the Salaf. Each then shows that the position's application of the principle is not consistent — it accepts ta'wīl where convenient and rejects it elsewhere; it does not allow <em>laysa ka-mithlihi shayʾ</em> to function as an indicator while accepting other verses in that role; it deploys kalām in practice while rejecting it in principle.</p>
  <p>None of this is to say the Salafī tradition has no scholarly content or that its concerns are illegitimate. The concern that any departure from the apparent meaning of a revealed text risks distortion is a serious one; the concern that kalām can lead its practitioners into philosophical errors that the Salaf would not have recognised is a serious one. The classical Sunnī position takes both concerns seriously — it does not authorise unrestricted ta'wīl or unconstrained kalām. What it adds is a more disciplined reading of the texts and a more precise account of when interpretive tools are necessary, anchored in the four-madhhab uṣūl al-fiqh tradition that the Salafī movement has substantially set aside.</p>

  <p>For topic-specific working out of these principles, see the topic pages on <a href="/topics/ibn-taymiyyah-aqidah">Ibn Taymiyyah and the ʿaqīdah of the Salaf</a> and <a href="/topics/ashari-maturidi-creed">the Ashʿarī &amp; Māturīdī schools</a>.</p>
